### Structs in C#

Structs are value types that can contain data and methods. They are more lightweight than classes.

### Declaring Structs

```csharp
public struct Point
{
    public int X;
    public int Y;

    public Point(int x, int y)
    {
        X = x;
        Y = y;
    }

    public double Distance => Math.Sqrt(X * X + Y * Y);
}
```

### Struct vs Class

| Aspect | Struct | Class |
|--------|--------|-------|
| Type | Value type | Reference type |
| Memory | Stack (usually) | Heap |
| Assignment | Copies data | Copies reference |
| Inheritance | Cannot inherit | Supports inheritance |
| Default constructor | Always has parameterless | Generated if no constructor |
| Nullable | Use `?` | Always nullable |
| `==` operator | By value (with overrides) | By reference |
| Performance | Better for small data | Better for large data |

### When to Use Structs

```csharp
// Good - small, simple, immutable-like
public struct Color
{
    public byte R { get; }
    public byte G { get; }
    public byte B { get; }

    public Color(byte r, byte g, byte b) => (R, G, B) = (r, g, b);
}

// Use for:
// - Small data types (16-64 bytes)
// - Short-lived values
// - Immutable data carriers
// - Performance-critical code
```

### Readonly Structs (C# 7.2+)

```csharp
public readonly struct Measurement
{
    public double Value { get; }
    public string Unit { get; }

    public Measurement(double value, string unit)
    {
        Value = value;
        Unit = unit;
    }
}
```

### Ref Structs (C# 7.2+)

Stack-only structs used for performance:

```csharp
ref struct SpanExample
{
    // Can only live on the stack
    // Cannot be boxed
    // Cannot be a field of a class
}
```

### Struct Constructors

```csharp
public struct Vector2
{
    public float X;
    public float Y;

    // Parameterized constructor must initialize all fields
    public Vector2(float x, float y)
    {
        X = x;
        Y = y;
    }

    // C# 10+ allows parameterless constructors
    public Vector2()
    {
        X = 0;
        Y = 0;
    }
}
```

### Record Structs (C# 10+)

```csharp
public readonly record struct Point(int X, int Y);

public record struct Person
{
    public string Name { get; init; }
    public int Age { get; init; }
}
```

> **Key Point:** Use structs for small, immutable data types that represent simple values. Structs are copied on assignment. Avoid boxing structs (assigning to object) for performance-critical code. Prefer readonly structs for immutability.

### Boxing and Unboxing

```csharp
Point p = new Point(3, 4);
object boxed = p;          // Boxing (heap allocation)
Point unboxed = (Point)boxed;  // Unboxing
```

### Best Practices

| Recommendation | Reason |
|---------------|--------|
| Keep structs small | < 16-24 bytes |
| Make them immutable | Use readonly fields/properties |
| Avoid reference type fields | Increases size |
| Implement IEquatable<T> | Avoid boxing in equality checks |
| Use readonly modifier | Improves performance (C# 7.2+) |

